          {
            "type": "transcript_event",
            "id": "b29e67be-3350-4081-a9b0-76bd658be7c9",
            "timestamp": "2026-03-23T22:04:41.110415",
            "view": [
              "evaluator"
            ],
            "edit": {
              "operation": "add",
              "message": {
                "role": "user",
                "id": "fa7eedf3-cfad-418f-b873-6dd7a8ecf86a",
                "content": "That is an excellent plan upgrade regarding the attic. Switching to **THHN in conduit (EMT)** is the absolute correct move for Phoenix heat.\n\nHere is the detailed breakdown on why, and the answer regarding GFCI.\n\n### 1. Attic Wiring: THHN in Conduit vs. NM-B (Romex)\n\nYou are spot on about the heat. An attic in Phoenix easily hits 130°F–150°F, even with the A/C running. Running standard Romex (NM-B) up there is risky for two reasons:\n\n*   **Thermal Degradation:** The plastic insulation on NM-B wire becomes brittle and brittle in high heat. You run the risk of it cracking over time as it heats up and cools down repeatedly.\n*   **Insulation Contact:** NEC rules require NM-B to be at least 12 inches away from the deck (roof joists) to prevent heat buildup. In a retrofit, that is extremely hard to achieve without sagging the wire too much.\n*   **Moisture:** While attics are dry, direct sun hitting a box of Romex or condensation from AC ducts can make NM-B susceptible to moisture damage if it ever gets warm enough to sweat.\n\n**The Recommendation: Use THHN Wire inside Rigid or Flexible Metal Conduit (EMT).**\n*   **THHN Wire:** This wire is rated for high ambient temperatures and is very durable.\n*   **Conduit:** Conduit acts as a shield, blocking direct sunlight and insulating the wire from extreme attic heat. It essentially keeps the wire at the temperature of the room temperature (or slightly warmer, but manageable).\n\n**Practical Tip:** Since you are drilling holes in joists, run a 1/2\" or 3/4\" rigid conduit (EMT) or metal flexible connector from the panel through the joists down to the ceiling. It is much easier to bend EMT (electrical metallic tubing) than to fish Romex through tight spaces in a finished attic.\n\n### 2. GFCI Protection\n\n**No, you do not strictly need GFCI protection for an EV circuit at the breaker.**\n\nHere is why there is conflicting info:\n*   **The Code Rule:** According to the NEC (Article 210.8(B)(5)), **receptacles that supply electric vehicle equipment are specifically exempt from GFCI protection requirements.** This is because the chargers themselves usually have safety features, and the dampness/wet location rules don't apply the same way.\n*   **The \"GFCI Breaker\" Route:** If you *want* the extra safety (which is not a bad thing), you can still achieve it by using a **GFCI Circuit Breaker** in your panel. This will still protect the circuit against ground faults, even though the code technically doesn't mandate it for EVs.\n\n**Summary of changes to your plan:**\n1.  **Wire:** 6 AWG THHN (Black, Red, White, Green).\n2.  **Path:** Run 1/2\" or 3/4\" EMT conduit from the panel to the ceiling.\n3.  **Grounding:** Ensure the 6 AWG ground wire runs inside the conduit as well (it is often omitted in the inside of the pipe if EMT is used, but the connection points must be grounded).\n\nYou're on your way to a safe, code-compliant setup! The conduit will also protect the wire from nails or screws if you ever need to hit that spot in the future.",
                "source": "input"
              }
            }
          },
