                "content": "### Panel Labeling Best Practices\n\nYou are doing the right thing by thinking ahead. A cluttered panel is a safety hazard.\n\n1.  **Standard White Stickers:** The industry standard is \"Level 1\" stickers. These are small white stickers with black text (often on a small blue background).\n2.  **Placement:** Stick them on the **face of the breaker** so the label is visible even if the panel door is closed.\n3.  **Content:** Write \"EV Charger 50A\" on the label.\n4.  **Duplication:** Don't just label the breaker. Take a marker and write \"EV Charger\" or \"40A\" directly onto the NEMA 14-50 outlet faceplate. If someone unplugs it and puts it in a drawer, or if you are troubleshooting later, you'll know instantly.\n5.  **Legend:** If you have a little extra space on your panel door, draw a tiny little diagram with lines pointing to the breaker and the outlet with the text \"EV Charger.\" This is extra helpful if the electrician doing future maintenance doesn't know what the car charger is.\n\n### The 40-Foot Run\n\n**Yes, 6 AWG is absolutely fine for a 40-foot run.**\n\n*   **Voltage Drop:** Electricity loses a tiny amount of \"push\" over distance, but with a short 40-foot run of thick copper 6 AWG, you will lose practically zero voltage.\n    *   6 AWG copper has very low electrical resistance.\n    *   For a 50A load over 40 feet, the voltage drop is less than 2 volts.\n    *   Your charger will see nearly full 240V, which is perfect for efficient charging.\n*   **Conduit:** 40 feet of 1/2\" or 3/4\" EMT is very manageable. Just make sure you don't have too many sharp bends (less than 360 degrees total, ideally) when you are threading the wire through the conduit.\n\n**One Final Tip for the Run:**\nSince you are drilling through the joists, try to run the conduit horizontally rather than vertically if possible. Horizontal runs protect the cable better from the attic temperature gradients (heat rising) and make it less likely to sag over time.\n\nYou are all set. Good luck drilling and labeling",
                "source": "input"
