                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "You are absolutely right to question that \"constant macros\" advice. While consistency is the king of adherence, **bioavailability is the queen of results.** If your training load is changing, your substrate requirements *must* change.\n\nFor CrossFit, you are manipulating the nervous system and the musculoskeletal system simultaneously. Periodizing carbs is the only way to match the energy demands of the heavy weeks and the adaptation demands of the deload.\n\nHere is how I would approach a 4-week mesocycle to maximize performance and metabolic flexibility:\n\n### The 4-Week Strategy: \"Load and Reload\"\n\n#### Weeks 1–3: The \"Fuel the Fire\" Phase (Nutrient Targeting)\nIn these weeks, volume and intensity are spiking. You are building muscle damage and glycolytic debt.\n*   **The Goal:** Maximize glycogen replenishment and provide substrate for tissue repair.\n*   **The Adjustment:** **Increase Carbs (specifically pre- and post-workout).**\n    *   **Target:** Add **30–50g net carbs** to the days with the highest WOD density.\n    *   **Why:** Your athletes are in a catabolic state due to fatigue. They need more \"mortar\" (carbs) to keep the \"bricks\" (muscle) together.\n    *   **The Trap:** Do not front-load everything on training days, or you will snap the IF streak. Push volume to rest days to make room for the extra fuel.\n\n#### Week 4: The \"Metabolic Reset\" Phase (Deload)\nThis is where a lot of coaches fail. They keep the high-carb diet going into a deload, leading to glycogen super-compensation without the stimulus to use it, or worse, weight gain.\n*   **The Goal:** CNS recovery, hormonal normalization, and metabolic flexibility training.\n*   **The Adjustment:** **Lower Total Carb Volume, Shift Timing.**\n    *   Since they are doing less work, their fuel needs are dropping, but their recovery needs are high.\n    *   **Strategy:** **Carb cycling.** Keep carbs high on the single high-intensity WOD day, but switch the athletes to \"fasted training\" or lower-carb eating on the lighter accessory/skill days.\n    *   **Why:** This forces the body to start oxidizing fat during the lighter days, improving metabolic flexibility without losing performance on the heavy day.\n\n### The \"Momentum\" Method\nYou don't want to shock their system too hard. Instead of vertical jumps in carb intake, aim for a 10–15% increase during the buildup.\n\n**Example of a Macro Shift:**\n*   **Baseline (Maintenance):** 250g Carbs / Day.\n*   **Weeks 1-3 (Build):** 275–300g Carbs / Day (Increase mostly on workout days).\n*   **Week 4 (Deload):** 250g Carbs / Day (Return to baseline to let the system normalize).\n\n### How to Sell This to Clients\nAthletes often fear that changing macros means they are \"failing\" or \"cheating\" on their diet.\n*   **Reframe it:** \"Weeks 1-3, we are stockpiling fuel so we can PR on Week 3. Week 4, we are clearing the pipes to make sure you feel fresh.\"\n*   **The Whoop Angle:** \"If you see your Recovery Score drop, don't adjust training. Adjust the carbs. Ensure your fuel is high enough to support the intensity you are asking for.\"\n\n### Summary\n*   **Weeks 1–3:** **Stay ahead of the deficit.** If the workout burns 400g glycogen, aim to replace 460g. Don't train in a deficit just because it's a \"workout day.\"\n*   **Week 4:** **Exploit the downtime.** Use the lower training load to maintain metabolic flexibility by lowering intake on lighter days."
