n### 4. Focus on \"Keeping Money in Tulsa\"\nThis bypasses environmental arguments entirely and appeals to pocketbooks.\n*   **The Pitch:** \"Right now, money leaves Tulsa every time we flip a switch. This proposal keeps those millions of dollars right here in the local economy, paying local contractors and local workers, while insulating us from the price hikes the big utility companies are about to announce.\"\n\n### 5. Management of the Skeptic at Public Meetings\nYou will have one person stand up and claim this is a \"liberal conspiracy\" or a waste of money. Here is how to handle them without getting a \"standing ovation\" yourself, but without validating them:\n\n*   **Don't argue with facts:** If they say, \"Solar doesn't work on cloudy days,\" don't say \"Actually, science says...\" Say: *\"That’s a fair point. That’s why we’re also including batteries and focusing on critical infrastructure first, so those buildings never lose power. We are hedging our bets.\"*\n*   **The \"Utility Bill\" Dealbreaker:** If the skeptic brings up cost, bring out the **ESPC** (Energy Savings Performance Contract) again.\n    *   *\"This costs the taxpayers zero up front. The money comes from the savings in our energy bills. If you don't like the concept of solar, you should love the concept of getting your city electric bill reduced.\"*\n\n### Summary Talking Points for Flyers/Ads\n*   **Headline:** **Keep the Lights On.** (Implies heat/water safety).\n*   **Sub-headline:** Solar panels on city roofs + Battery storage = Resilience for the whole neighborhood.\n*   **Bottom line:** **Zero Cost to Taxpayers.**\n\n**Pro Tip:** When you hold a town hall, bring a **simple dashboard app** (like EnergyHub) that shows real-time energy usage from just *one* city building. Seeing the live numbers go down when the sun comes up is the most powerful tool you have to convince the room that this works.",
