                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "You are asking the right question. When you are at that town hall or presenting to colleagues, you need \"back-of-the-envelope math\" that feels real, not marketing fluff.\n\nSince we are in 2025, solar technology costs have plateaued but remain competitive. Here is a realistic breakdown you can use to pitch specific buildings.\n\n### The \"Tulsa Math\" Formula\nFor a quick mental estimate, use these 2025 averages for the Tulsa area:\n*   **Installation Cost:** Roughly **$2.50 to $3.00 per Watt**.\n*   **Solar Production:** A typical 1 kW system (about 3-4 panels) generates roughly **1.4 to 1.6 kWh of electricity per day**.\n*   **Local Electric Rate:** In Tulsa, commercial rates hover around **$0.13 to $0.14 per kWh**.\n\n**The Quick Formula:**\n> **(1 kW Solar System Cost) ÷ (Savings per kWh)** = **Years to pay for itself.**\n\n*Example:* If a 1 kW system costs $3,000 and saves roughly $1.85 worth of electricity per day, it pays for itself in about **4.5 years**.\n\n---\n\n### Real-World Scenarios for Tulsa Buildings\n\nHere is what you can realistically project for two common types of municipal buildings in Tulsa:\n\n#### Scenario 1: Mid-Sized Office or Fire Station (~15,000 - 25,000 sq ft)\n*   **Usage Profile:** Moderate, but heavy AC usage in July/August.\n*   **The Math:** You’d likely install a **40 to 60 kW solar system**.\n*   **The Investment:** roughly **$150,000 to $200,000** (ESPC paid by contractor).\n*   **The Savings:**\n    *   You can expect this system to offset **70% to 80% of the building’s annual electric bill**.\n    *   For a building spending $250-$300/month on power, that's a savings of roughly **$1,800 - $2,500 per month**.\n    *   **Headline:** \"A 60 kW system pays for itself in 5 years and saves the city $1,700 a month instantly.\"\n\n#### Scenario 2: Large Community Center or Recreation Center (~50,000 sq ft)\n*   **Usage Profile:** High load. Lights, water pumps, and massive AC usage.\n*   **The Math:** You’d likely install a **200 to 250 kW system**.\n*   **The Investment:** roughly **$750,000 to $900,000**.\n*   **The Savings:**\n    *   You can expect to offset **85% to 90% of the building’s usage**.\n    *   **Headline:** \"A 250 kW system covers 85% of the building's energy, saving roughly $12,000 - $15,000 per month. Over 10 years, that's over $1.5 million saved.\"\n\n---\n\n### The \"Skeptical\" Questions to Prep For\n\n**\"But won't the panels get ruined in hail?\"**\n*   **Answer:** \"We will specify High-Impact Resistant (HIR) rated panels. They are much stronger than standard residential panels and are required in many commercial applications now. Plus, the money we save pays for better equipment.\"\n\n**\"What happens when it's cloudy/rainy?\"**\n*   **Answer:** \"Solar produces energy in direct and indirect light. Even on a cloudy day, Tulsa gets decent UV and diffused light. Plus, the sun hits the panels at a different angle than the windows, which keeps them cooler and more efficient.\"\n\n**\"What about the batteries? Isn't that extra cost?\"**\n*   **Answer:** \"Batteries are expensive, so we'll phase them in. For the first 2 years, we focus on the solar panels. Once the system is proven, we add the batteries to ensure that facility never loses power during a storm.\"\n\n### The \"Golden Number\" to Quote\nIf you want a single number to throw out that sounds impressive but is defensible, use **\"80-90% energy offset.\"**\n\nSaying \"We will save 90% of the bill\" is believable because buildings have predictable usage patterns (lights on from 8 AM to 5 PM), and solar hits hard during the exact middle of that day (12 PM - 2 PM).\n\nGood luck, Council Member Hendricks. You’ve got a solid plan here."
                  }
